<span class="openapi-clients-box"><span class="openapi-clients-box-heading">Clients</span><a href="https://docs.apify.com/api/client/python/reference/class/DatasetCollectionClientAsync#list" target="_blank"><img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/apify/openapi/b1206ac2adf8f39b05e5a09bf32c2802af58d851/assets/python.svg" class="openapi-clients-box-icon" alt="Apify API Python Client Reference"/></a><a href="https://docs.apify.com/api/client/js/reference/class/DatasetCollectionClient#list" target="_blank"><img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/apify/openapi/b1206ac2adf8f39b05e5a09bf32c2802af58d851/assets/javascript.svg" class="openapi-clients-box-icon" alt="Apify API JavaScript Client Reference" /></a></span><span id="/reference/datasets/dataset-collection/get-list-of-datasets"></span><span id="/reference/datasets/get-list-of-datasets"></span>Lists all of a user's datasets. The response is a JSON array of objects,
where each object contains basic information about one dataset.
By default, the objects are sorted by the `createdAt` field in ascending
order, therefore you can use pagination to incrementally fetch all datasets while new
ones are still being created. To sort them in descending order, use `desc=1`
parameter. The endpoint supports pagination using `limit` and `offset`
parameters and it will not return more than 1000 array elements.
